<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="user-interviews">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>ux</group>
    <domain>ux-ui-designer</domain>
    <summary>One-on-one conversations with users to understand needs, behaviors, motivations, and pain points. Qualitative and exploratory; reveals the "why" behind observed behaviors.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>user-research</tag>
      <tag>interviews</tag>
      <tag>qualitative</tag>
      <tag>discovery</tag>
      <tag>insights</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>User Interviews</title>
    <summary>User interviews are one-on-one conversations with users or potential users to understand needs, behaviors, motivations, and pain points. They are qualitative and exploratory — they reveal the "why" behind observed behaviors. 5-8 participants per distinct user segment is the practical threshold for theme saturation.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Designing without user input replaces understanding with assumptions. Assumptions produce wrong solutions to real problems or correct solutions to non-existent ones. User interviews are the primary method for developing genuine empathy with users before design decisions are made.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Discovery phase — understand the problem space, user needs, mental models</item>
        <item>Design phase — validate concepts and early-stage ideas before prototyping</item>
        <item>Post-launch — understand how users actually use the product and what frustrates them</item>
        <item>Generating a tailored interview guide from research objectives and user profile descriptions</item>
        <item>Synthesizing interview transcripts or notes into themes and insight statements</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Quantitative goals (frequency, statistical significance) — use surveys or A/B testing</item>
        <item>Conducting the interview itself — an agent cannot replicate human facilitator judgment or rapport</item>
        <item>Replacing user research entirely — agent synthesis requires actual interview data as input</item>
        <item>When participants cannot provide informed consent for AI processing (check privacy regulations)</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="interview-types">
      <p>Exploratory (45-60 min) — understand the problem space and user needs. Generative (30-45 min) — generate ideas about possible solutions. Evaluative (30-45 min) — test concepts or early-stage designs. Contextual (60-90 min) — observe users in their actual environment.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Write research questions (what you need to learn) before writing interview questions (what you will ask).</statement>
        <rationale>Starting with interview questions produces survey-like guides; starting with research objectives produces guides that follow the user's answers.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="recruitment-criteria">
      <p>5-8 participants per distinct user segment is the practical threshold for theme saturation. Recruit from: customer database, user panels, social media, professional recruiters. Mix demographics; include both current users and prospects.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="question-design">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use open-ended questions that ask about past behavior, not hypothetical future behavior.</statement>
        <rationale>Hypothetical questions ("would you use...") produce aspirational answers, not behavioral evidence. Past behavior predicts actual usage.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>"Tell me about the last time you [did X]." — anchors to a specific real experience with retrievable detail.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad">
        <note>"Would you use a feature that does Y?" — hypothetical; users say yes to be helpful, not because they would actually use it.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <note>"Walk me through your typical process for [task]." — generates behavioral context the designer can act on.</note>
      </example>
      <example type="bad">
        <note>"Don't you think the app is too complicated?" — leading; suggests the answer and biases the response.</note>
      </example>
      <p>Probing follow-ups: "Why do you think that happened?", "Can you give me a specific example?", "Tell me more about that."</p>
    </section>
    <section name="synthesis-techniques">
      <p>Affinity mapping: write each observation on a separate note, group similar notes, name each group, identify patterns across groups. Insight statement format: "[User type] needs [need] because [motivation/reason]. Currently, [pain point/gap]."</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Separate "what users said" from "what we infer" in every insight statement.</statement>
        <rationale>Collapsing observation and inference produces insights that sound like research findings but are actually interpretations; stakeholders cannot challenge what they cannot see the evidence for.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="facilitation-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Listen more than talk; the interviewer's words should be fewer than 20% of the session transcript.</statement>
        <rationale>Talking more than the participant signals that the interviewer is not genuinely curious, closing down disclosure and producing thin data.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Do not react positively or negatively to answers; stay neutral throughout.</statement>
        <rationale>Positive reactions (nodding, "great!") bias subsequent answers toward what the interviewer appeared to reward; neutrality preserves honest disclosure.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Record sessions (with consent) even when taking notes.</statement>
        <rationale>Notes miss quote-level detail; transcripts enable the evidence-backed synthesis that makes findings credible to stakeholders.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-synthesis-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always provide verbatim source material when asking the agent to "find examples" or extract quotes.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent will hallucinate plausible-sounding quotes if not given actual transcript text; synthesis must be grounded in provided source.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Insight statements synthesized by agent must be validated against source notes by the researcher before sharing with stakeholders.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent may introduce framing bias when rewriting observations into insights; researcher validation is the quality gate.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Sanitize transcripts (replace participant names with IDs) before passing to external LLM APIs.</statement>
        <rationale>Interview transcripts often contain PII; participant privacy must be protected under applicable regulations.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Poor recruitment — interviewing participants who do not match the target user profile.</description>
        <reason>Insights from the wrong users produce design decisions that serve a population that does not exist or will not use the product.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Not probing — accepting surface-level answers without follow-up.</description>
        <reason>First answers are often rehearsed or socially acceptable; the real insight lives in the follow-up ("why is that?", "can you give me an example?").</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>No analysis — collecting data without synthesizing it into insights and sharing with the team.</description>
        <reason>Unanalyzed interview data has zero design impact; synthesis is not optional.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A Claude subagent receives research objectives, target user profile, and project context, and outputs a structured Interview Guide (intro script, warm-up, main question blocks, wrap-up). After interviews, a second agent pass receives raw session notes (one file per participant) and performs synthesis: extracts key quotes, identifies recurring themes, generates HMW (How Might We) questions, and produces an insight statement per theme.</p>
      <rule>
        <statement>Agent-generated interview guides tend toward closed or mildly leading questions when the product context is provided — require explicit review for question neutrality before use.</statement>
        <rationale>LLMs default to product-focused framing; true neutrality requires human designer review against research objectives.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Synthesis from notes is bounded by what the interviewer wrote down; if the interviewer summarized instead of quoting, the agent will synthesize summaries, not evidence.</statement>
        <rationale>Note quality determines synthesis quality. Thin notes produce thin insights. Require verbatim quotes in session notes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Agent may introduce framing bias when rewriting observations into insights — always verify synthesized statements against source quotes.</statement>
        <rationale>Agent's paraphrasing may subtly shift the meaning of the original observation. Validation by the researcher is mandatory before stakeholder handoff.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="tools-and-services">
      <text>
CLI tools and services for interview support:

Whisper (OpenAI) — Local audio transcription of recorded interviews. Install: pip install openai-whisper / https://github.com/openai/whisper

ffmpeg — Convert audio/video formats before transcription. Install: apt install ffmpeg / https://ffmpeg.org

otter.ai CLI — Automated transcription service (no official CLI; use API). https://otter.ai/developers

Dovetail — Qualitative research repository; no CLI, but REST API for importing transcripts and tagging. https://dovetail.com/developers/

User Interviews (userinterviews.com) — SaaS for participant recruitment and scheduling; API for managing studies. Partial agent-friendliness.

Dovetail (SaaS) — Import transcripts, create highlights, tag themes via API; best qualitative repo for agent integration. Yes, agent-friendly via REST API.

Otter.ai (SaaS) — Automatic transcription; REST API for fetching transcript text. Yes, agent-friendly via API.

Maze (SaaS) — Unmoderated research; interview-style question blocks; results export as CSV. Partial agent-friendliness.

Lookback (SaaS) — Moderated interview platform; session recordings exported manually. No direct API.

Notion (SaaS) — Store interview notes and synthesized findings; agent can create/update pages via API. Yes, agent-friendly via API.

Airtable (SaaS) — Track participants, sessions, and recruitment status programmatically. Yes, agent-friendly via API.
      </text>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Write the research questions (what you need to learn) before writing interview questions (what you will ask) — this prevents guides that feel like surveys</item>
        <item>Pilot the guide with one internal teammate before running participant sessions; adjust question order and timing</item>
        <item>Record sessions (with consent) even when taking notes — transcripts enable quote-level analysis that notes miss</item>
        <item>5-8 participants per distinct user segment is the practical threshold for theme saturation; do not over-recruit</item>
        <item>Present synthesis to stakeholders with verbatim quotes attached to each insight — data without evidence is not persuasive</item>
        <item>Separate "what users said" from "what we infer" in every insight statement — agent is particularly prone to collapsing this distinction</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using agent-generated interview guides without neutrality review.</description>
        <reason>Agent-generated guides tend toward closed or mildly leading questions when product context is provided. Require explicit review for question neutrality before use.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Expecting agents to conduct interviews themselves.</description>
        <reason>Agent cannot replicate a human facilitator's rapport, body language reading, or real-time probing judgment. Interviews must be human-facilitated.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Relying on agent synthesis without validation against source notes.</description>
        <reason>Human-in-loop checkpoint: insight statements must be validated against source notes by the researcher before being shared with stakeholders or used for design decisions.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Asking agent to "find examples" without providing verbatim transcript text.</description>
        <reason>Agent may hallucinate quotes if asked to "find examples" without being given the actual transcript text. Always provide verbatim source material.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Passing unredacted transcripts to external LLM APIs.</description>
        <reason>Privacy: interview transcripts often contain PII. Ensure transcripts are sanitized (participant names replaced with IDs) before passing to external LLM APIs.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/interview-guide.md" purpose="Full interview guide: intro script, warm-up, main topics, probe suggestions, wrap-up"/>
      <template path="templates/session-notes.md" purpose="Per-session notes: quotes, observations, pain points, needs, behaviors"/>
      <template path="templates/transcribe-sessions.sh" purpose="Bash script for batch-transcribing recordings with OpenAI Whisper"/>
    </templates>
    <see-also>
      <link href="https://www.nngroup.com/articles/user-interviews/"/>
      <link href="https://www.interaction-design.org/literature/article/how-to-conduct-user-interviews"/>
      <link href="https://www.userinterviews.com/ux-research-field-guide-chapter/user-interviews"/>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
